posts.content:
Last week, I wired $2.7M to buy back control of my companies. Not from investors, not from an agency‚Äìfrom a partner who'd joined just last year. 

Those 8 digits hitting their account marked the final chapter of my 10-year, $5.2M journey to 92% ownership of Groove and Helply.

It started with the classic partnership playbook.

First the vision: "We'll scale this together, take it to new heights."

Then reality: Our paths just weren't aligned.

No hard feelings‚Äìjust a $2.7M reminder that sometimes the best partner is yourself.

It was a heavy wire to send.

But, it made me reflect on what really matters: shared control and true ownership.

Because here's something partners don't seem to understand:

I've spent 10 years buying back $5.2M in equity because I believe in running this my way.

I'm not building for exits. I'm building for my family.

We're wildly profitable (50%+ EBITDA), growing steadily (without the unicorn chase), and delivering exactly what I want ($5M ARR, complete control, zero pressure). That's the whole point.

If you're running a profitable bootstrapped SaaS business in 2025, you can choose your path.

In today's world, if you can grow sustainably‚Äìyou don't need anyone's permission to build it your way.

When your timeline is generational, you can either chase other people's dreams or buy back every single percentage point until it's truly yours. I choose ownership. I choose family.

I choose the long game.

In this market, partnership offers mean nothing if you're building for your children's children.

Here's to another 10, 20, 30 years of grinding‚Äìmy way, at 92% ownership and counting.

Like you, I‚Äôve learned that shared vision and alignment are everything in small organizations and shareholders. When they‚Äôre not there, it‚Äôs better to part ways and double down on your own path. Building with clarity and purpose‚Äîwithout external pressures‚Äîis what leads to real, sustainable success.

Struggling to Speak Up? Let‚Äôs Talk About It.

Ever stayed silent in a meeting because you weren‚Äôt *100% sure* your idea was good enough?

Or stopped yourself from asking a question because you thought you should already know the answer?

It‚Äôs not just fear of judgment‚Äîit‚Äôs the high expectations we set for ourselves.

You think, If I don‚Äôt say something perfect, it‚Äôs better to say nothing at all.
Sound familiar?

This is how imposter syndrome keeps us quiet.

We convince ourselves that if we can‚Äôt meet an impossible standard, we shouldn‚Äôt even try.

Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learned‚Äîand what I tell my clients:

1Ô∏è‚É£ **You‚Äôre not expected to be perfect.**
Most of the time, people don‚Äôt remember how ‚Äúflawless‚Äù your input was‚Äîthey remember that you contributed.

2Ô∏è‚É£ **Your high standards are holding you back.**
Trying to get everything right before you speak up often means you miss the chance altogether. Remember, *progress beats perfection.*

3Ô∏è‚É£ **Focus on learning, not proving.**
Ask yourself, *‚ÄúWhat can I gain by sharing this?‚Äù* instead of worrying about what others might think.

4Ô∏è‚É£ **Practice speaking up, even in small ways.**
Start with one idea or question in a casual setting. The more you do it, the easier it gets.

Your voice matters‚Äînot because it‚Äôs perfect, but because it‚Äôs *yours.*

Have you ever felt this way? How do you push through it? Share your thoughts below‚ÄîI‚Äôd love to hear them.
posts.commentAdded: Great insights! Its so true that progress trumps perfection. Fostering open dialogue can empower us all. Lets keep speaking up!

Alex Turnbull
posts.content:
Does less engineers = more productivity?

Old Engineering Motion:

- Hiring targets are standard so we can grow every quarter without thinking
- Build massive teams - we'll get efficient eventually
- The VP ran Engineering at BigTech, they're perfect for our growing business
- Of course they need 7,000+ people to get things off the ground
- The growth model says we'll hit unicorn status
- Teams send over forecasts, Finance chases them, productivity drops a year later
- We have a planning meeting every month but neither Product or AI joins
- We need to pay engineers massive compensation in every region
- Our efficiency metrics are upside down, let's hire more engineers!
- "Just build a bigger team!"

New AI-First Motion (The Salesforce way, apparently‚Ä¶):

- We're building an Agentforce-led business
- Cut engineering hires by 100% in 2025
- Productivity increased by 30% with AI
- We have an "AI-first" engineering team that Benioff says "has incredible velocity"
- They don't want more engineers. Together they're proving AI can boost productivity, not just assist
- Engineering, Product, AI and Sales meet regularly to identify more automation opportunities
- The success of the business is built around AI not headcount
- Every role is measured against one metric: can AI do it better?

In a world where Salesforce's productivity jumps 30% while cutting engineering hires completely, is aligning your team around AI-first development smart, or is it just survival?

Or beyond survival, does it mean thriving?

The math is pretty clear:
‚Ä¢ 2023: 7,000 layoffs to increase efficiency
‚Ä¢ 2024: 700 more cuts with AI integration
‚Ä¢ 2025: No more engineering hires, +2,000 salespeople

My feelings are mixed as it was with the Klarna news last month (interesting these press releases were made within a week of each other‚Ä¶).

But I like to consider myself a realist.

How do you all feel about this? Would love to hear from engineers and founders alike...

comments.commentText:
Time will tell if all of this is hot air or not.

In my experience, writing the code was never the bottleneck.

Discussing what to build, how to build it, rebuilding because of misunderstanding or change in priorities, having to adapt to ongoing architecture changes or update something old because of a new security requirement... These were all timesinks that LLMs can't help much in.

"We doubled the number of engineers but our rate of output hasn't doubled" was a phrase I heard far too often. Like duhhhh at some point something else becomes more important than headcount.

posts.commentAdded: Fascinating shift! Embracing AI-first development could redefine productivity norms. Excited to see how this impacts engineering roles moving forward!
